nsducer resonant frequency\nand the number of SSHC stages.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 30 Sep 2019 04:33:32 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 19 Nov 2021 00:35:06 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-11-22"}
{"id":"1909.13454","submitter":"Doyeol (David) Ahn","authors":"Sang-Eon Bak, Paul M. Alsing, Warner A. Miller, Shahabeddin M.\n  Aslmarand and Doyeol Ahn","title":"Quantum information theoretic study of scrambling effect on de Sitter\n  horizon","comments":"19 pages, 5 figues","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph gr-qc","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Scrambling effect on de Sitter horizon, which is a fundamental problem yet to\nbe resolved, is studied from a quantum information theoretic point of view. We\nfirst study the evolution of quantum correlation in spacetime for three\nmaximally entangled states. The effect of the expansion is described by an\noperator sum representation with the corresponding Kraus operator. It is shown\nthat this map is a trace-preserving and complete positive map. It is found that\nthe quantum effect in de Sitter spacetime can be represented as a noisy quantum\nchannel by using these two properties. We suggest that our analysis of the\nrelation between bipartite mutual information and tripartite mutual information\ncan be viewed as a specific model to show the scrambling effect in de Sitter\nspacetime. For large expansion rate, there exists a small magnitude of the\nbipartite mutual information when the magnitude of the tripartite mutual\ninformation is large. This is congruent to the fact that scrambling means the\ndifficulty of information recovery from the local measurement. Therefore, we\nconclude that there is a scrambling effect in de Sitter spacetime.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 30 Sep 2019 04:48:53 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 10 Oct 2019 07:05:57 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 15 Sep 2022 03:47:21 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-09-16"}
